<tr style=3D"height:105.4pt">
<td colspan=3D"2" style=3D"width:440.45pt; border:solid windowtext 1.0pt; b=
order-top:none; padding:0cm 5.4pt 0cm 5.4pt; height:105.4pt" valign=3D"top"=
 width=3D"440">
<p class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin-bottom:12.0pt; text-align:justify; t=
ext-justify:inter-ideograph; text-autospace:none">
<span class=3D"hps"><strong><span style=3D"font-family:&quot;Kohinoor Devan=
agari Medium&quot;; color:black" lang=3D"HI">=E0=A4=B8=E0=A4=BE=E0=A4=B0</s=
pan></strong></span><span class=3D"hps"><strong><span style=3D"font-family:=
Arial; color:black" lang=3D"HI">/Abstract</span></strong></span><span style=
=3D"font-family:Arial; color:black" lang=3D"HI">
</span><span style=3D"font-family:Arial; color:black">The computation of th=
ermodynamic properties of a system is often hard to do in an infinitely lar=
ge, or even a very large system, especially in the quantum case, due to the=
 exponential growth of the state space.
 In order to make useful claims from a study of small finite systems, one h=
as to have a good estimate of the &quot;finite size&quot; errors. In this t=
alk, I will discuss how these errors scale in such calculations, and show t=
hat we can minimize these errors if we use
 linked cluster expansions. I will also discuss an application of this appr=
oach to a quantum dynamics problem where we study the phenomenon of many bo=
dy localization.</span></p>
</td>
